  <a href="#1" id="1">
   (08/04/1987) The National Union of Mineworkers said an estimated 200,000 black gold and coal miners in South Africa will begin a strike on 08/09/1987 night for higher wages and better working conditions, in what it said would be the largest job action ever to affect the mining industry in that nation.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   (07/21/1989) Coal miners in Siberia ended their strike on 07/21/1989 after exacting promises of better food, housing and working conditions, but the wave of unrest they launched continued in other key coal regions.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   (07/21/1989) In the largest coal region, the Donetsk Coal Basin of the Ukraine, more than 300,000 miners were on strike, the deputy minister of the coal industry, Alexander P. Fisun, told Izvestia.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   (07/21/1989) Gorbachev has expressed sympathy for the strikers and placed much of the blame for the miners' deteriorating working and living conditions on leaders of the officially sanctioned trade unions.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   (11/03/1989) Thousands of miners in the northern Vorkuta region are expanding their strike and some are blocking coal shipments, the Soviet news media reported on 11/03/1989.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   (11/03/1989) Coal miners in the northern region and the Ukraine struck for two weeks this summer but returned to work in July after parliament passed a resolution promising reforms, including improved social and economic conditions.
  </a>
